    <!-- SCIENCE SECTION -->
    <h2 id="science">The Science Behind Maca Root: What Clinical Research Shows</h2>

    <p>Maca root benefits from a growing body of human clinical trials — a distinguishing factor in the often poorly-researched supplement landscape. The evidence supports specific claims at specific doses, and understanding these distinctions helps consumers choose the right product for their goals.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Libido: strong evidence</strong>
        <p>Multiple RCTs show increased sexual desire in both men and women at 1,500 to 3,000mg daily for 6 to 12 weeks, independent of hormone level changes (Andrologia, 2002; CNS Neuroscience, 2008).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Energy and stamina: moderate evidence</strong>
        <p>Maca improved endurance performance in trained cyclists by 3.5% at 2,000mg daily for 14 days. Mechanism involves enhanced mitochondrial biogenesis (J Ethnopharmacol, 2009).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Menopause symptoms: moderate evidence</strong>
        <p>Two clinical trials showed reduced hot flashes, improved mood, and decreased anxiety at 2,000 to 3,500mg daily for 6 to 12 weeks in postmenopausal women (Menopause, 2008; Int J Biomed Sci, 2006).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Fertility: emerging evidence</strong>
        <p>Black maca specifically increased sperm count by 200% and motility by 30% in a 2009 Andrologia study. Human fertility trial data is still limited but promising.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A landmark 2002 RCT published in <em>Andrologia</em> enrolled <strong>57 healthy men</strong> and administered 1,500mg or 3,000mg of maca daily for 12 weeks. Both dose groups reported <strong>significantly increased sexual desire</strong> starting at week 8 compared to placebo — critically, without any measurable changes in serum testosterone or estradiol levels. This finding indicates maca works through <strong>non-hormonal pathways</strong>, likely involving the endocannabinoid and dopaminergic systems.</p>
      <cite>Gonzales et al., Andrologia, 2002 — 57 participants, 12-week RCT</cite>
    </div>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
      <p><strong>Important context:</strong> While maca has a strong safety profile, individuals with thyroid conditions should exercise caution. Maca contains glucosinolates, which are goitrogenic compounds that could theoretically interfere with thyroid function at very high doses. Current clinical evidence does not show thyroid disruption at standard supplementation doses (1,500 to 3,000mg/day), but monitoring is advisable for those with existing thyroid conditions.</p>
    </div>

