    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Maca Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is maca root and what are its benefits?</summary>
      <p>Maca root (<em>Lepidium meyenii</em>) is a cruciferous vegetable native to the high Andes of Peru, grown at elevations above 4,000 meters. It has been used for over 2,000 years as a food and medicinal plant. Modern research has identified bioactive compounds called macamides and macaenes that support energy production, hormone balance, libido, fertility, and mood regulation. Unlike synthetic hormones, maca works as an adaptogen that helps the body regulate its own endocrine function.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between red, black, and yellow maca?</summary>
      <p>The three main maca phenotypes differ in their bioactive profiles. Yellow maca is the most common variety, supporting general energy and mood. Red maca has been studied for prostate health and bone density, and is considered the most antioxidant-rich variety. Black maca shows the strongest evidence for libido enhancement, sperm production, and cognitive function. A 2009 study in <em>Andrologia</em> found that black maca specifically improved sperm count and motility, while a separate study showed it enhanced memory and learning.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Does maca actually increase libido?</summary>
      <p>Yes, multiple clinical trials support maca's effect on sexual desire. A 2002 double-blind RCT published in <em>Andrologia</em> found that men taking 1,500mg to 3,000mg of maca daily for 12 weeks reported significantly increased sexual desire compared to placebo, independent of changes in testosterone or estradiol levels. A 2008 <em>CNS Neuroscience and Therapeutics</em> study confirmed similar effects in women taking antidepressants, showing improved libido scores at 3,000mg daily.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can maca help with menopause symptoms?</summary>
      <p>Research supports maca's role in managing menopausal symptoms. A 2006 study in the <em>International Journal of Biomedical Science</em> found that maca reduced menopausal symptoms including hot flashes, mood swings, and sleep disturbances in postmenopausal women over 12 weeks. A 2008 <em>Menopause</em> journal study showed that 2,000mg of pre-gelatinized maca daily for 6 weeks reduced anxiety and depression scores while improving sexual dysfunction in early postmenopausal women.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How long does it take for maca gummies to work?</summary>
      <p>Most users report noticeable improvements in energy and mood within one to two weeks of consistent daily use. Libido and sexual function changes typically become apparent at the four to six week mark. Hormonal balancing effects, including improvements in menstrual regularity and menopausal symptoms, generally require six to twelve weeks of sustained supplementation. Consistency is essential — clinical studies showing positive results used maca for a minimum of six weeks.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is maca safe to take every day?</summary>
      <p>Maca has an excellent safety profile in clinical research. Doses of 1,500mg to 3,000mg daily have been used safely in trials lasting up to 12 weeks with no significant adverse effects. Maca is classified as a food by the Peruvian government and has been consumed as a dietary staple for millennia. Individuals with thyroid conditions should consult their healthcare provider, and pregnant or breastfeeding women should seek medical guidance before supplementing.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What dose of maca should I look for in gummies?</summary>
      <p>Clinical studies showing benefits typically used 1,500mg to 3,000mg daily. Many gummies provide 500mg to 1,500mg per serving. Gelatinized or concentrated maca extracts may be effective at lower absolute doses because the processing concentrates bioactive compounds and improves absorption by up to 400%. Look for products specifying the maca form and whether the dose reflects raw root equivalent or concentrated extract.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Does maca affect testosterone levels?</summary>
      <p>Multiple clinical studies found that maca improved sexual desire and energy without directly changing serum testosterone levels. However, black maca specifically increased sperm count and motility in a 2009 <em>Andrologia</em> study, suggesting reproductive hormone modulation at the tissue level. Maca appears to enhance hormonal signaling efficiency rather than increasing raw hormone production, acting as an adaptogenic modulator.</p>
    </details>

